%S A396867 3,15,84,420,5460,87780,1141140,19399380,562582020,13831757940,
%T A396867 401120980260,14841476269620,608500527054420,29994623540902020,
%U A396867 1229779565176982820,65178316954380089460,3975877334217185457060,257649886920664493635380,15716643102160534111758180
%N A396867 Least negated fundamental discriminant -D of imaginary quadratic fields such that omega(-D) = n, where omega = A001221.
%C A396867 For n >= 3, a(n) is divisible by 4 but not by 8. See my link "Terms of A396867" below for a proof.
%C A396867 For n >= 0, the least -D such that the class group of real quadratic field with discriminant D has 2-rank n (A319659) is a(n+1).
%H A396867 Jianing Song, <a href="/A396867/b396867.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..350</a>
%H A396867 Jianing Song, <a href="/A396867/a396867_2.txt">Table of n, a(n)/(4*p_2*...*p_n) for n = 3..10000</a>.
%H A396867 Jianing Song, <a href="/A396867/a396867_1.txt">Terms of A396867</a>.
%F A396867 Let p_i = prime(i), q_i = A002144(i) be the i-th prime congruent to 1 modulo 4, and r_i = A002145(i) be the i-th prime congruent to 3 modulo 4. Suppose that {p_2, ..., p_n} = {q_1, ..., q_{n-1-m}} U {r_1, ..., r_m}. Write N = 4*p_2*...*p_n. For n >= 3:
%F A396867 - If m is even, then a(n) = N.
%F A396867 - If m is odd, then a(n) is either (q_{n-m}/r_m)*N or (r_{m+1}/q_{n-1-m})*N (i.e., obtained by either removing the largest prime <= prime(n) congruent to 1 modulo 4 and adding the least prime > prime(n) congruent to 3 modulo 4, or removing the largest prime <= prime(n) congruent to 3 modulo 4 and adding the least prime > prime(n) congruent to 1 modulo 4).
%F A396867 See my link "Terms of A396867" above.
%e A396867 For n = 3, we have {3, 5} = {q_1=5} U {r_1=3}. Since the number of primes congruent to 3 modulo 4 is odd, a(n) is the minimum between 4*5*13 and 4*3*7, which is 4*3*7 = 84.
%e A396867 For n = 7, we have {3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17} = {q_1=5, q_2=13, q_3=17} U {r_1=3, r_2=7, r_3=11}. Since the number of primes congruent to 3 modulo 4 is odd, a(n) is the minimum between 4*5*13*17*29*3*7 and 4*5*13*3*7*11*19, which is 4*5*13*3*7*11*19 = 1141140.
%o A396867 (PARI) a(n) = {
%o A396867 if(n==1, return(3));
%o A396867 if(n==2, return(15));
%o A396867 my(N=4, res=1, plim=prime(n), q, r);
%o A396867 forprime(p=3, plim, N=N*p; res=(res*p)%4; if(p%4==1, q=p, r=p)); \\ N = 4*p_2*...*p_n, q is the largest prime <= p_n congruent to 1 mod 4, r is the largest prime <= p_n congruent to 3 mod 4
%o A396867 if(res==1, return(N)); \\ if the number of primes <= p_n congruent to 3 mod 4 is even, then a(n) = N
%o A396867 forprime(p=plim+1, oo, if(p%4==3, q=p/q; break())); \\ smallest prime > p_n congruent to 3 mod 4
%o A396867 forprime(p=plim+1, oo, if(p%4==1, r=p/r; break())); \\ smallest prime > p_n congruent to 1 mod 4
%o A396867 return(N * min(q,r));
%o A396867 }
%Y A396867 Cf. A002144, A002145, A319659.
%Y A396867 See A396868 for the case of real quadratic fields.
%K A396867 nonn
%O A396867 1,1
%A A396867 _Jianing Song_, Jun 08 2026
